description:
Inspired by Google Docs version history and Sudowrite draft experiments.

Problem: writers fear large edits because rollback is difficult.
Outcome: writers can experiment safely and recover prior versions in seconds.
Acceptance criteria:
- Users can create named snapshots and browse automatic timeline checkpoints.
- Diff preview highlights inserted/deleted paragraphs before restore.
- Restore action creates a new head version without destructive overwrite.
- Snapshot metadata includes timestamp, author, and change summary.

Assign to: Market Research

<plan>

## Goal

Implement a version timeline with draft snapshots and restore for the story editor. Users gain a persistent, browsable history of their writing with auto-checkpoints every 5 minutes and the ability to manually name and save named drafts. Any version can be previewed in a read-only panel and restored with a one-click flow that first saves a safety snapshot of the current content.

---

## Scope and files

### New files (6)

| Path | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `src/lib/versions.ts` | Storage layer: read/write `story_{storyId}_versions` in localStorage, enforce 50-auto-checkpoint retention cap, safety-snapshot-before-restore logic |
| `src/hooks/useVersionHistory.ts` | React hook: owns 5-minute auto-checkpoint timer (useRef), exposes versions list, handlers for add/restore/name-draft |
| `src/components/VersionHistory/VersionHistory.tsx` | Drawer panel component: version list, preview pane, name-draft input |
| `src/components/VersionHistory/VersionHistory.module.css` | Styles for all sub-elements of the drawer |
| `src/components/VersionHistory/VersionEntry.tsx` | Single row in the version list (timestamp, word count, label, Preview/Restore actions) |
| `src/components/VersionHistory/VersionPreview.tsx` | Read-only textarea pane with "Restore from this version" button |

### Modified files (2)

| Path | Changes |
|---|---|
| `src/app/story/[id]/page.tsx` | Add `isHistoryOpen` state; add "History" button in `editorHeader`; mount `<VersionHistory>` overlay; add `handleVersionRestore` callback wiring into `useVersionHistory` and `useAutosave` |
| `src/app/story/[id]/page.module.css` | Add `.historyButton`, `.historyButtonActive`, `.editorDimmed`, `.historyOverlay` classes |

---

## Step-by-step plan

### Step 1 — Define the `VersionEntry` type

Create `src/lib/versions.ts`. At the top, export the interface:

```typescript
export interface VersionEntry {
  id: string;           // crypto.randomUUID()
  content: string;
  timestamp: number;    // Date.now()
  label: string | null; // null = auto-checkpoint
  type: 'auto' | 'named';
  wordCount: number;    // counted at save time
}
```

Add a private helper `countWords(content: string): number` — split on whitespace, filter empty strings, return length.

Add a private key helper: `versionsKey(storyId: string) => \`story_${storyId}_versions\``.

### Step 2 — Implement `getVersions` and `saveVersions` in `src/lib/versions.ts`

```typescript
export function getVersions(storyId: string): VersionEntry[]
```
- Read `versionsKey(storyId)` from localStorage.
- Parse JSON; return `[]` on error or missing.
- Sort: named entries first (by timestamp desc), then auto entries (by timestamp desc). This matches the design brief's "named drafts pin to top".

```typescript
function saveVersions(storyId: string, versions: VersionEntry[]): void
```
- Private. Write JSON string to `versionsKey(storyId)`.
- Swallow write errors (same defensive pattern as `autosave.ts`'s `saveSnapshot`).

### Step 3 — Implement retention enforcement in `src/lib/versions.ts`

```typescript
function enforceRetention(versions: VersionEntry[]): VersionEntry[]
```
- Keep all `type === 'named'` entries unconditionally.
- From `type === 'auto'` entries: sort by `timestamp` desc, keep the 50 most recent, drop the rest.
- Return the combined array (named + trimmed auto), sorted named-first then by timestamp desc.

### Step 4 — Implement `addAutoCheckpoint` in `src/lib/versions.ts`

```typescript
export function addAutoCheckpoint(storyId: string, content: string): VersionEntry
```
- Call `getVersions(storyId)`.
- If the most recent auto entry (sorted by timestamp desc) has the same `content`, return early without writing — guard against no-op checkpoints.
- Build a new `VersionEntry` with `type: 'auto'`, `label: null`, `id: crypto.randomUUID()`, `timestamp: Date.now()`, `wordCount: countWords(content)`.
- Push onto array, call `enforceRetention`, call `saveVersions`.
- Return the new entry.
- Wrap in try/catch; log on error, rethrow so the caller can handle.

### Step 5 — Implement `addNamedVersion` in `src/lib/versions.ts`

```typescript
export function addNamedVersion(storyId: string, content: string, label: string): VersionEntry
```
- Same pattern as `addAutoCheckpoint` but `type: 'named'`, `label: label.trim()`.
- No content-equality guard — user explicitly triggered this.
- Call `enforceRetention` (named drafts are never dropped, but keep it consistent for future-proofing).
- Return the new entry.

### Step 6 — Implement `restoreVersion` in `src/lib/versions.ts`

```typescript
export function restoreVersion(
  storyId: string,
  versionId: string,
  currentContent: string
): VersionEntry | null
```
- First: call `saveSnapshot(storyId, currentContent)` from `@/lib/autosave` — this is the safety snapshot before any destructive action.
- Also call `addAutoCheckpoint(storyId, currentContent)` — create a checkpoint of what is being replaced so the user can get back to "where I was before restore".
- Find the `VersionEntry` by `id` in `getVersions(storyId)`.
- Return the entry (caller uses `.content` to replace editor state), or `null` if not found.

### Step 7 — Create `src/hooks/useVersionHistory.ts`

```typescript
'use client';

import { useState, useEffect, useRef, useCallback } from 'react';
import {
  getVersions,
  addAutoCheckpoint,
  addNamedVersion,
  restoreVersion,
  type VersionEntry,
} from '@/lib/versions';
import { saveSnapshot } from '@/lib/autosave';

interface UseVersionHistoryOptions {
  storyId: string;
  content: string;          // current editor content (read by timer)
  onRestore: (content: string, version: VersionEntry) => void;
}

interface UseVersionHistoryResult {
  versions: VersionEntry[];
  hasVersions: boolean;
  saveNamedDraft: (label: string) => void;
  restoreToVersion: (versionId: string) => void;
  refreshVersions: () => void;
}

export function useVersionHistory({
  storyId,
  content,
  onRestore,
}: UseVersionHistoryOptions): UseVersionHistoryResult
```

Implementation details:

- `const [versions, setVersions] = useState<VersionEntry[]>(() => getVersions(storyId))` — load on mount.
- `const contentRef = useRef(content)` then `contentRef.current = content` in render — same pattern as `useAutosave`'s `contentRef`, avoids stale closure in the timer.
- `const lastCheckpointContentRef = useRef<string>('')` — tracks what content was at the last checkpoint so the timer can skip no-op fires.
- `const checkpointTimerRef = useRef<ReturnType<typeof setInterval> | null>(null)` — never useState for timers (from prior Code Reviewer feedback).

5-minute timer via `useEffect`:
```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  checkpointTimerRef.current = setInterval(() => {
    const currentContent = contentRef.current;
    if (currentContent !== lastCheckpointContentRef.current && currentContent.trim() !== '') {
      addAutoCheckpoint(storyId, currentContent);
      lastCheckpointContentRef.current = currentContent;
      setVersions(getVersions(storyId));
    }
  }, 5 * 60 * 1000);

  return () => {
    if (checkpointTimerRef.current) clearInterval(checkpointTimerRef.current);
  };
}, [storyId]);
```

`saveNamedDraft(label: string)`:
- Guard: `label.trim()` must not be empty.
- Call `addNamedVersion(storyId, contentRef.current, label)`.
- Call `setVersions(getVersions(storyId))`.

`restoreToVersion(versionId: string)`:
- Call `restoreVersion(storyId, versionId, contentRef.current)` — gets the version entry back (safety snapshot is done inside `restoreVersion`).
- If entry is non-null, call `setVersions(getVersions(storyId))`, then call `onRestore(entry.content, entry)`.

`refreshVersions()`:
- `setVersions(getVersions(storyId))` — used by the panel when it opens to ensure fresh data.

Return `{ versions, hasVersions: versions.length > 0, saveNamedDraft, restoreToVersion, refreshVersions }`.

### Step 8 — Build `src/components/VersionHistory/VersionEntry.tsx`

Props:
```typescript
interface VersionEntryProps {
  entry: VersionEntry;
  onPreview: (entry: VersionEntry) => void;
  onRestore: (versionId: string) => void;
}
```

Render structure:
- Outer `<div>` with `role="listitem"`, hover class from `.entryRow`.
- Left: label text (if `entry.label`, render bold in `--color-black-700`; else "Auto-checkpoint" in `--color-cement-400`), then below: `formatRelativeTime(entry.timestamp)` (import from `@/lib/autosave`), absolute date in a `<time>` element as `title` attribute for hover tooltip.
- Right: word count (`{entry.wordCount} wds`), then "Preview" button and "Restore" button.
- "Restore" uses `--color-carbon-600` bg + `--color-white` text per design brief.

Accessibility: both buttons have descriptive `aria-label` including the timestamp (e.g. `aria-label="Preview version from 3m ago"`) so screen reader users can distinguish entries.

### Step 9 — Build `src/components/VersionHistory/VersionPreview.tsx`

Props:
```typescript
interface VersionPreviewProps {
  entry: VersionEntry;
  onRestore: (versionId: string) => void;
  onClose: () => void;
}
```

Render:
- Back arrow button "Back to history".
- Header showing entry label or "Auto-checkpoint" + `formatRelativeTime(entry.timestamp)` + `{entry.wordCount} wds`.
- Read-only `<textarea>` with `readOnly`, `value={entry.content}`, `aria-label="Version content preview"`.
- "Restore from this version" button at bottom (dark bg, white text).
- This is v1 — no diff view, just the full version content.

### Step 10 — Build `src/components/VersionHistory/VersionHistory.tsx`

Props:
```typescript
interface VersionHistoryProps {
  versions: VersionEntry[];
  onRestore: (versionId: string) => void;
  onSaveNamedDraft: (label: string) => void;
  onClose: () => void;
}
```

Internal state:
- `const [previewEntry, setPreviewEntry] = useState<VersionEntry | null>(null)` — which entry is being previewed.
- `const [draftLabel, setDraftLabel] = useState('')` — the "Name this draft" input value.
- `const closeButtonRef = useRef<HTMLButtonElement>(null)` — focus on mount.

Structure:
- Outer `<aside>` with `role="complementary"`, `aria-label="Draft History"`, CSS class `.panel`.
- Panel header: "Draft History" heading + close button (X), close button focused on mount (`useEffect`).
- If `previewEntry !== null`: render `<VersionPreview>` in place of the list, with `onClose={() => setPreviewEntry(null)}`.
- Else: version list as `<div role="list">`, each `<VersionEntry>` component. If `versions.length === 0`, render an empty state ("No checkpoints yet — keep writing!").
- Bottom section (always visible when in list view): `<input type="text" placeholder="Name this draft…">` + "Save draft" button. On submit: if `draftLabel.trim()` is non-empty, call `onSaveNamedDraft(draftLabel)`, clear the input.

Keyboard: Escape key listener closes panel (calls `onClose`). Same pattern as `ConfirmDialog`.

Named drafts render before auto-checkpoints — the `getVersions` sort in the lib layer handles this, so the component just renders `versions` in order.

